## ğŸ–¥ï¸ **Forms of Servers** (by **hardware or setup**):

| **Form**                | **Description**                                                                                            |
| ----------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| ğŸ–¥ï¸ **Physical Server** | A real, dedicated machine running server software.                                                         |
| ğŸŒ **Virtual Server**   | A server running **inside** another machine using virtualization (e.g. using VMware, VirtualBox).          |
| â˜ï¸ **Cloud Server**     | A virtual server hosted on a cloud provider (e.g. AWS, Azure, Google Cloud).                               |
| ğŸ§± **Rack Server**      | A flat server designed to fit into server racks in data centers.                                           |
| ğŸ“¦ **Tower Server**     | Looks like a traditional PC but works as a server. Used in small businesses.                               |
| ğŸ§° **Blade Server**     | A slim, modular server that fits into a chassis with shared power and cooling. Used in large data centers. |

---

## ğŸ§ª Summary:

* A **server** provides services or data to **clients**.
* It can serve **web pages**, **emails**, **files**, **databases**, etc.
* It comes in different **types** (web, mail, DB...) and **forms** (physical, virtual, cloud...).

